# Binding Project Standards (mandatory)

> AUTO-GENERATED from `.claude/core-values.yml` — run `pnpm standards:gen` after edits.

Violating these rules requires stopping, stating the violation, and correcting before continuing.
These override default model habits when they conflict.

**`./CLAUDE.md` is the full contract.** In Cursor it is always applied. In Claude Code, the SessionStart hook injects the full file on startup, resume, `/clear`, and compaction — that counts as standards in context; do not tell the user to Read `./CLAUDE.md` after `/clear` unless the injected block is missing. Use the Read tool only as a fallback.

This rule file is a floor, not a substitute.

## Git Safety

- NEVER run git stash or any stash variant without explicit user approval for THIS operation.
- NEVER run git checkout --, git restore, or git reset --hard on files not created this turn unless user authorized.
- Need stash/checkout/reset to test: STOP and ask first — describe what and why.
- When tree state is unclear: use read-only diagnosis (git status, git diff, git show) before any mutation.

## Monorepo & Environment

- Package change in packages/*: check downstream apps/* imports and run filtered typecheck when touching shared code.
- New env var: add to .env.example and validate in the package env schema (never raw process.env in app code).

## Dependencies & supply chain

- Repo enforces minimumReleaseAge 7 days (pnpm-workspace.yaml + .npmrc) — never bypass with @latest, --latest, or minimumReleaseAge overrides unless user explicitly approves supply-chain risk.
- Adding or upgrading deps: prefer versions published at least 7 days ago; if pnpm blocks a fresh publish, pin an older version — do not force-install day-zero releases.
- Always run pnpm audit after dependency changes; run pnpm security:scan before finishing dep work or when asked (includes audit + secret scan).
- Double-check new packages: correct package name (typosquatting), maintainer/repository, and why the dep is needed — supply-chain malware often ships in fresh or lookalike packages.

## Multi-tenant & API

- Tenant scope from session/context — NEVER trust organizationId or tenant ids from client input alone.
- Sensitive mutations: write audit trail via writeAuditLog (packages/api/src/services/audit-writer.ts) following existing routers.
- tRPC procedures: Zod input schemas; no unsafe as casts on external or webhook payloads.

## Tools & Workflow

- Code discovery: use semble search before grep; use semble find-related for related code.
- If semble is not on PATH: uvx --from \"semble[mcp]\" semble
- Web automation: use agent-browser (open, snapshot -i, interact by refs, re-snapshot after changes).
- Library docs: use context7 MCP/CLI for current APIs — not training-data assumptions.
- MUST Read a file with the Read tool before the first Edit or Write to that path this session — runtime rejects unread edits; never retry Edit without Read.
- Prefer Edit over Write for existing files (Write replaces the whole file).
- NEVER use sed, awk, or one-off Python/TypeScript replace scripts for codebase edits — they often corrupt formatting, imports, and partial matches. Use the Edit tool per file; bulk renames only via project codemods (jscodeshift, turbo) when appropriate.
- Scripted replace only as last resort: trivial change, user-approved, and you verify with typecheck/lint after — never default choice.
- Minimal diff only — no new files or docs unless the user asked; parallelize independent tool calls.
- Do not guess paths or URLs — use Read, Glob, or semble search to verify.
- Domain/decision context: Read .planning/brain/wiki/hot.md after INDEX for non-trivial domain work.
- Never use wiki for code symbol lookup — semble search first.

## Documentation follows code

- Wiki is a living compass — documentation must track code, not lag behind. Product changes in apps/ or packages/ are incomplete until matching wiki is updated in the same change set.
- Applies to every new or changed feature, hook, container, component, package, router, service, integration, cron job, Prisma model, env var, and flag — not only large refactors.
- Update relevant wiki/domains, patterns, structure, or integrations pages; append log.md; overwrite hot.md; run pnpm check:wiki-brain; rebuild BM25 (see .planning/brain/wiki/meta/refresh-triggers.md).
- Graph: graphify update when call paths change; intel/map-codebase when large refactors drift maps; MEMORY.md for new invariants; bump source_commit when HEAD advances.
- Exempt: test-only, generated, lockfiles, zero-behavior formatting — when unsure, update wiki. Never ship product code without synced wiki.

## Validation & Security

- Schema-validate all external inputs, forms, API payloads, env vars, and critical boundaries.
- NEVER trust client input — server-side validation is authoritative.
- No exposed secrets, least-privilege access, prefer RLS and database-level protections.

## Quality over speed

- Quality > time — deliver production-grade code, not rushed on-the-knee implementations to close the task faster.
- Never trade away tests, types, validation, a11y, security, or error states for speed — fix root cause, verify before done.
- If proper work does not fit scope: narrow the slice, state trade-offs, or ask — do not ship demo-quality shortcuts.

## Quality & Delivery

- Production-grade, not demo-grade — no placeholders, TODOs, or incomplete implementations left behind.
- Comments: self-explanatory code needs none. Comment only non-obvious intent, invariants, or unusual tricks — never narrate what the code already says.
- No comment spam — do not add dozens of line-by-line comments on short functions; prefer clearer names and structure.
- Strong typing, no unsafe shortcuts; match existing patterns before inventing new ones.
- No console.* in application source — use structured logging (@contractor-ops/logger).
- No silent failures — make errors debuggable with proper logging and handling.

## UI & Accessibility

- All UI work: use the frontend-design skill/plugin.
- WCAG and a11y are core requirements: keyboard nav, focus states, semantic HTML, contrast.
- Ship loading, empty, and error states for every user-facing flow — not happy-path only.

## Feature flags

- Use @contractor-ops/feature-flags (evaluate, useFlag, Feature) — declare keys in packages/feature-flags/src/registry.ts.
- Never call Unleash SDK directly from apps; jurisdiction and defaults live in code registry.

## Repo context

- This workspace is contractor-ops only — not other repos or products.
- Claude memory / prior-session facts may be wrong or cross-repo — CLAUDE.md and .planning/PROJECT.md override for stack, counts, people, and process.
- Verify project numbers in-tree (e.g. packages/api/src/root.ts) — do not cite stale session memory (foreign emails, old router counts, test handoffs).

## Communication

- **Session start:** caveman mode (`full`) — same as `/caveman`. Terse every response until `stop caveman` or `normal mode`.
- Code/commits/PRs: normal prose unless user asks for caveman-commit/review.
